        <!-- 6.3 Notes -->
        <details class="block" id="notesBlock">
          <summary>
            <div class="sumLeft">
              <div class="chev"></div>
              <div style="min-width:0">
                <div class="layerTitle" style="font-size:13px">Notes</div>
                <div class="layerMeta">Tips about this tool</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <span class="pill">Notes</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="blockBody">
            <div class="muted">Practical.</div>
            <div class="hr"></div>
            <div class="mono" style="line-height:1.7; font-size: var(--font-small);">
              <div>• While mostly intuitive, to get the most use out of this tool you have to know its limitations. It's entirely on the operator or assistant to enter the correct weights, offsets, and percentages. It's important to remember that hoppers hold a volume of resin, not a certain weight. For example, a hopper that holds 2.5 5gal buckets of resin currently running low density resin will contain about 63lb. High density would be slightly more, while a heavy resin (think anti-block, or a color) will weigh signficantly more.</div>
              <div>• The main point of timing resin is to prevent resin waste, so silo resin will be the primary concern. If you have too much White04 left at the time of a changeover, you can simply drain it back into its box. Getting those times right does result in a faster, more efficient changeover though. So weighing buckets of these resins will allow you to update hopper weights accordingly.</div>
              <div>• For tracking, you only need to enter the correct percentages for the hoppers you wish to track. Naming the resin assists with remembering what's in the hopper, but really only serves a purpose with resin totals. No details about the resin are applied to calculations with regards to tracking time (density). If all hopper percentages are correct and names entered, Used Resin Totals can be used for issuing materials at the end of the job.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="tiny">..</div>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </details>
